A user types [www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com) in the browser.

First DNS translates the domain name to the IP address of the load balancer. After that the request goes to HAProxy through HTTPS.

I added a load balancer because if one server has a problem the other one can still work. It also shares the traffic between servers.

HAProxy uses Round Robin. It sends the first request to server 1, the second request to server 2, then continues like that.

This is an Active-Active setup because both servers are working and receiving requests.

Each server has:

* Nginx
* Application server
* Application files
* MySQL

I added firewalls to protect the servers and block unwanted connections.

I added an SSL certificate because HTTPS encrypts the traffic between the user and the infrastructure. This helps protect sensitive data.

I added monitoring clients to collect information about the servers. They can collect CPU usage, memory usage, disk usage and service status and send it to a monitoring service.

Monitoring is useful because it helps find problems quickly and keep track of the health of the servers.

If I want to monitor web server QPS, I can collect data from Nginx logs or Nginx metrics and see how many requests are processed every second.

The MySQL databases work in a Primary-Replica configuration. The Primary database accepts write operations and the Replica receives copies of the data from the Primary.

The difference is that the Primary can handle INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE operations while the Replica is mainly used for reading and backup.

Problems with this infrastructure:

* SSL termination on the load balancer can be a problem because traffic between the load balancer and the servers may not be encrypted.
* Only one MySQL server accepts writes. If the Primary fails, write operations stop working.
* Having the same components on all servers can waste resources and make management more difficult.
* The load balancer is still a SPOF because if it goes down users cannot reach the servers.
